column1: Before 1 January 2021, will Tesla release an Autopilot feature designed to navigate traffic lights?
column5: ['Before 1 July 2020', 'Between 1 July and 30 September 2020', 'Between 1 October and 31 December 2020', 'Not before 1 January 2021']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology']

I spent a long time in bucket 1, now I'll spend the rest of the time in bucket two. A price increase on July 1 would imply the feature is availbale July 1 and later. Perhaps the revenue from the feature will be booked in Q3 instead of Q2. If you are curious: https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-full-self-driving-price-increase-july-1/
Edit: hedging more aggressively.
Adjusting...

Well if we are talking about the "Full Self Driving" update, we now have a price hike date. But hey, to those of you saying, "wait, wasn't this resolved in March?" I'm with you: " FSD works with the car's Autopilot suite and includes a number of features, including automatic lane changes, parallel and perpendicular parking assist, the bring-the-car-to-me summon feature, Navigate on Autopilot highway driving assistance and most recently, ***automatic traffic light and stop sign control***. The next bit of software in the FSD suite will allow the car to automatically steer on city streets, as well. "

Right, our dear friend... Ambiguity. I suppose it is irrational to *presume* the interpretation of the question - so yes, I am hedging against whether it is deemed that "the future is now" but still holding out for the true intention lending itself to a holiday release of a wider feature suite.

FWIW: Still waiting on a clarification or "ruling" promised by GJP about the following (as a possible resolution for this question). I will follow-up again shortly, but the lack of a ruling or clarification makes me start thinking about 'hedging' my forecast a little bit:

I am loosing my nerve on this one. The beta release will provide lots of passenger miles of new data to help train the neural networks for the full release. Given that the neural networks can continue to train on additional data, I would expect periodic updates throughout the feature's life. The incentive to full release is that would release funds to be booked as revenue that have been accruing since the feature was first sold.
Ot has been announced by Elon Musk that it will be available before year end. It may be used as part of a strategy to get sales in an economic downturn.
Announcements are out that a beta version was part of the 2020.12.6 software release in the US [1,2,3] on 4/24 [4]. It appears it was announced as part of the Q1 earnings call [3].
I am now questioning the ambiguity of the question.
It appears the update is available, in Europe the update has been detected. See update below

If I were Elon I would want to release a sign/ light recognition update when the lighting was perfect and the feature would have the best chance of being successful. That's the summer, not in the winter or wetter weather. Pre July 1 and under current covid conditions I'm not sure many people will care and that sentiment might carry through all of 2020
Not time yet.
It's going to be difficult to develop new features with COVID-19 going on. Plus Elon has a history of making promises he can't keep.

The person (or machine) who tells the operator of any kind of vehicle what to do to stay on course and out of trouble is a navigator. If Tesla has a program that does this, it is navigating. If it actually slows the vehicle down, it is doing even better than navigating. If the nice people who wrote this question meant the program had to have full operating control of the vehicle, they should have said so. Words have meanings.
https://electrek.co/2020/04/24/tesla-autopilot-traffic-light-and-stop-sign-control-feature/

Assuming the technology is ready this year, Tesla will most likely be motivated to roll it out late, to have people in the streets testing it and to avoid having its marketing efforts shadowed by the virus.

Following @jayb here [1,2]. Let's see if it is accepted as resolution or if we get a clarification.

More news articles reporting that Tesla is now rolling out a new version of Autopilot to some (non-test fleet) owners that " ...will allow (their vehicles) to see and respond to traffic lights and stop signs".

Below: Three linked articles from recent days, claiming that Tesla's latest Autopilot update (2020.12.6) now being released (to some owners) "...includes an update to Autopilot that enable vehicles to automatically react to traffic lights and stop signs".

If this comes out this year, it won't be until COVID calms down slightly. The movement of this feature to testing (https://tiresandparts.net/news/parts/tesla-working-on-new-autopilot-update-to-help-recognize-traffic-lights/) doesn't seem to indicate how well it is working.
Moving forecast a little closer to the 'crowd' for now, though an update of Autopilot that recognizes traffic signals has reportedly already been released to Tesla's "early access fleet" (users).

Elon Musk has a track record of over promising and underdelivering. Secondly software development itself is notoriously tricky and very costly. Auto Pilot features are very hard to deliver safely and are hard even by software standards.

I’m under the impression that Tesla’s abilities to come up with smart solutions in the car industry are dramatically over estimated. A modern car is a complex machine and a lot of experience goes into it. And for example the Chinese with all their engineering prowess are not able to simply copy a Porsche or BMW. And Tesla operates under the restrictions of the US capital market regime.
Changed forecast based on [1]. Still sceptical if it's actually going to happen.

From my research it looks as though Tesla has the technology in place already to launch the feature at short notice. However, common sense dictates that the feature go through rigorous testing before it is launched. This article says that the feature should be launched in the US within a matter of weeks: https://electrek.co/2020/04/03/tesla-release-autopilot-intersection-navigation-weeks-us-months-worldwide/.

Following @Coastal and @jayb lead I'll vote optimistically that TSLA can do this in 2020. With a lot fewer people on the road the next few months what a great time to beta test it. I mean how hard can it be to pick out a green or red light in your 180 degree field of view moving at 40MpH in the driving rain and get at least two cameras to agree?
